es. The story is told within the broader context of the different political, social and economic cultures from which modern nursing arose. Although the Russians were battling industrialised armies with their pre-industrial, agrarian economy it was they who developed the most innovative system of nursing. The book illustrates the barriers, some of which still exist today, which nurses had to overcome to gain recognition of the crucial role they played in the war. The significant contributions allied and Russian nurses made working directly under fire during the Russians’ brilliant defence of Sevastopol make a wonderfully exciting story during which these mid-nineteenth century nurses proved their extraordinary competencies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrimean War, 1853-1856xMedical care. 0aMilitary nursingxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aDeterminants of health.  aFeldshers.  aHumanitarianism.  aMale soldier nurses.  aMid-nineteenth century British military nursing.  aMid-nineteenth century French military nursing.  aMid-nineteenth century Ottoman army medical department.  aMid-nineteenth century Piedmont-Sardinian military nursing.  aMid-nineteenth century Russian military nursing.  aMid-nineteenth century heath care.  aNineteeth century military nursing.  aNursing and constructions of gender.  aNursing and domestic service.  aNursing and social status.  aNursing education and clinical experience.  aPatient perspectives of medical and nursing care.  aReligious nurses.  aSecular lady nurses.  aSystems of nursing.  aTransnationalism.  aWorking-class nurses.1 aHelmstadter, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez9783111282